<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">level tho the outlet seems So inadequate<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  There is certainly a slow but periodical rising and falling of the Lake no way affected by external circumstances yet discovered<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  But it has not had that attention paid to it the Phenomenon merits<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Old Inhabitants say the Term is Seven years but of this there is no possitive proof<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The beach from the last mentioned Point is much lower than the Sandy Mountain being Seldom more than 20 or 30 feet above the level of the Lake and has nothing Remarkable except a small Vein of fine freestone beautifully tinged with Red blue and green, which is about two leagues from the Point, and One, to the commencement of <span class="AddHand-author">the</span> Precipices call'd by the French the Portails or Facades<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Here the coast tends more to the West and begins gradually to rise from ten to at least 200 feet, the Rock is a white freestone perfectly perpendicular and in a distance of three Leagues has three little Bays <span class="DelHand-author">almost</span> nearly at equal distances placed by the hand of Providence to insure Safety and encourage the navigation of <span class="AddHand-author">a coast</span> otherwise not to <span class="AddHand-author">be</span> attempted in almost any Season or circumstances<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">About half a league from where the Rocky coast forms an Angle with the sand beach there is a pretty little waterfall which breaks from among the Trees and tumbles in foam down the Side</p>

